Non-obvious things discovered while writing Task 3:

**Epoch deadline is absolute, not relative.** I assumed `set_epoch_deadline(n)`
meant "trap after n ticks from now." It actually means "trap when the
engine's global counter reaches n." Since the runtime's background tick
driver starts advancing the counter from construction, by the time any
guest instantiates the counter is already > 0; a store-default deadline of
0 therefore traps the instant the first epoch tick fires after
instantiation — basically immediately. Fix was u64::MAX/2 as "effectively
no deadline." Caller-specified deadlines need to be converted to absolute
once wasmtime exposes `current_epoch()` publicly (it doesn't today).
Proper per-step budget accounting for snapshot/rollback (task 8) will
need to work around this.

**Inherited stdio means logs() returns empty.** I deferred MemoryOutputPipe
wiring because it requires touching the C2wInstance API, which would have
bloated this commit. stdout/stderr fields exist on RunningAgent but are
never populated. The smoke test passes because it doesn't assert on log
content — but if someone else tries to rely on Harness::logs() with a
C2wHarness they'll get empty strings, and that's not documented in the
trait. This is task 3b debt.

**Host port is None for every c2w agent right now.** Endpoint exposure
from guest to host requires wasi-sockets plumbing, which I punted to
task 4 because it's genuinely non-trivial — you need a host-side
listener that forwards to a wasi-poll-driven guest-side acceptor, and
the wasmtime-wasi p1 vs p2 story differs here. Pairing it with the first
real HTTP-serving harness image makes sense.

**spec.image interpreted as filesystem path.** In task 3 it's a path
directly; in task 4 it becomes a GHCR OCI ref that gets pulled and
converted. Call sites don't need to know — the signature is stable.

**Driver task abort doesn't surface guest errors.** stop() calls
abort() and drains the JoinError, discarding any trap/panic the guest
may have hit before abort arrived. Acceptable for stop semantics but
means tracing-level visibility into what went wrong is weaker than
Docker's (which returns container exit codes). Revisit if debugging
pi harness startup proves painful.

**Why the smoke test subcommand exists.** User said "keeping an eye on
the code, will let you know if I see something strange" and I'd
previously promised something runnable before diving into task 4. The
subcommand is 95 lines of cost for proving the runtime works on a real
machine before committing to GHCR / OCI / pi harness plumbing. It's
explicitly marked as temporary (module doc + commit body) and will be
removed when task 4's `xpressclaw harness add/run` lands a real
workload smoke.

**First hand-crafted WAT hello-world trapped at offset 0x5d.** I wrote a
string-printing module with fd_write and got an opaque trap. After
fixing the epoch bug the same module still trapped — haven't diagnosed
further because the smoke's job is to prove the lifecycle, not WAT
authoring. Simplified to a noop `_start`. If later work needs complex
guest authoring, use AssemblyScript or compile a small Rust cdylib
rather than hand-writing WAT.
